From: Michal Koutný <mkoutny@suse.com>
Date: Wed, 4 Dec 20:01:44 +0100
Subject: mm: memory.stat allow preemption
References: bsc#1231877
Patch-mainline: Never, upstream has rstat

Collecting data for memory.stat on systems with many memcgs may take a while
and this all happens without preemption in kernel.
Reading memory.stat can happen at will by user proceses so it can negatively
impact kernel threads that would need to run given CPU.
Add a preemption point between each processes memcg, this will decrease
precision of memory.stat values (the closer to root, the more) but assuming
memory.stat is for information or debugging and not for control decisions, this
should be fine.

Upstream kernel did several reworks that moved some of the accounting work to
the writers' side but eventually converted this in the commit 2d146aa3aa842
("mm: memcontrol: switch to rstat") to rstat mechanism of cgroups. Those are
too many too big changes to have in SLE12-SP5.

Signed-off-by: Michal Koutný <mkoutny@suse.com>
---
 mm/memcontrol.c |    2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

--- a/mm/memcontrol.c
+++ b/mm/memcontrol.c
@@ -2796,6 +2796,8 @@ static void accumulate_memcg_tree(struct
 		for (i = 0; i < NR_LRU_LISTS; i++)
 			acc->lru_pages[i] +=
 				mem_cgroup_nr_lru_pages(mi, BIT(i));
+
+		cond_resched();
 	}
 }
 
